Description: Fix CVE-2026-44487 - Proxy-Authorization header leak on redirect
 The Node.js HTTP adapter could forward a Proxy-Authorization header to a
 final origin server during a proxy-to-direct redirect transition. When an
 initial http:// request goes through an authenticated proxy and the
 redirect target is no longer proxied (e.g., no HTTPS_PROXY matches, or
 NO_PROXY applies), the stale proxy credential could leak to the
 redirected origin.
 .
 This patch is an inline backport of the upstream v1.x fix
 (axios/axios@afca61a) adapted to the v0.21.4 code structure. It:
   * adds a removeProxyAuthorization() helper that strips all case
     variants of the Proxy-Authorization header,
   * adds a resolveEnvProxy() helper that reuses shouldBypassProxy for
     NO_PROXY evaluation on redirect targets,
   * extends setProxy() with an isRedirect flag so stale credentials are
     scrubbed on redirect re-invocation,
   * re-resolves proxy applicability for each redirect target inside
     beforeRedirect, so when the redirect target should not be proxied the
     stale Proxy-Authorization is removed and the request is routed directly,
   * exposes __setProxy and __removeProxyAuthorization for unit tests.
 Test-file hunks were removed because tests are not present in the published
 npm tarball (dist-based patching applies to lib/ only).
